{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493389"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:08:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:08:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1309"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1309"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.12,0.36,0.26,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1309"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32962"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1309"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1309"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18439"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"556"},{"type":"tags","id":"645"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8334"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8623"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15062"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18479"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46509"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49528"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32962","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/32962"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 21-year-old man presents to the emergency department complaining of deep central abdominal ache which started about two hours earlier. These are the only symptoms he has and is otherwise in good health. He is rather coy about talking as to how his symptoms might have started. A plain abdominal radiograph is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following physical signs was most likely to be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Palpable abdominal mass","Hypoactive bowel sounds","Vibrating umbilicus","Abdominal distension","Ecchymosis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cause of this patient\u0027s symptoms are fairly clear from the X-ray and with further discussion, he sheepishly admitted that he had been \u0027playing with himself.\u0027 Colorectal foreign bodies are a not uncommon presentation to the emergency department. In this case, the patient has voluntarily inserted a vibrator through the anus into the rectum for sexual stimulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epalpable abdominal mass \u003C/strong\u003Emay be found on examination in larger foreign bodies and ones high in the rectum, but in this case this is less likely. Of course most rectal foreign bodies are palpable in the distal rectum on digital rectal examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is unlikely for \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypoactive bowel sounds\u003C/strong\u003E to be present as these are a non-specific finding of bowel obstruction which is a very rare complication of foreign bodies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely sign to be present is a \u003Cstrong\u003Evibrating umbilicus\u003C/strong\u003E as the patient has inserted a powered vibrator into their rectum. This which would transmit vibrations through the tissue of the abdomen and indeed in this case, a gentle hum could be heard and vibrations noticed at the umbilicus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EColorectal foreign bodies do not typically cause \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal distension.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEcchymosis \u003C/strong\u003Emay be present if there was significant retroperitoneal or intraperitoneal haemorrhage but in this case there is no reason to suspect such a complication.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Foreign bodies in the rectum should be confirmed by plain abdominal radiograph and rectal examination"],"references":["Jackson D, Mayou B. Vibrating umbilicus BMJ 1973; 2:780Jun 30;2(5869):780. doi: 10.1136/bmj.2.5869.780-c."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18439"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1309"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19292"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19292"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cd59e522-3471-4096-9013-fe4e8c01ee6f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cd59e522-3471-4096-9013-fe4e8c01ee6f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":378,"height":461}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/18439"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-02-24T14:32:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-02T09:56:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1309"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32962"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},